post.title: what do you think is more relevant to your personality and behavior: The founding fathers or a great great great grandfather from the 18th century?the

body: A great great great grandfather, if my math is correct, would account for 1 32nd of my dna. Assuming I’d still be born if you switched him out for someone completely different, how would my life change? I’d maybe be hair darker or lighter skinned/haired, not enough to change my life-experiences significantly. My genetic dispositions might be somewhat different, but probably not greatly. My personality, life choices, and core beliefs would likely be much the same. On the contrary, switch the founding fathers out for wildly different people, and the entire world I grew up in would be unrecognizably different. My core political and even personal beliefs might well never have been formed without their example. Even the founders I least agree with provide good foils to the beliefs I do hold.
body_html: A great great great grandfather, if my math is correct, would account for 1 32nd of my dna. Assuming I’d still be born if you switched him out for someone completely different, how would my life change? I’d maybe be hair darker or lighter skinned/haired, not enough to change my life-experiences significantly. My genetic dispositions might be somewhat different, but probably not greatly. My personality, life choices, and core beliefs would likely be much the same. On the contrary, switch the founding fathers out for wildly different people, and the entire world I grew up in would be unrecognizably different. My core political and even personal beliefs might well never have been formed without their example. Even the founders I least agree with provide good foils to the beliefs I do hold.
